---
export const prerender = true;

import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "API Calls and Server Endpoints";
const description = "Learn how API endpoints work in Astro compared to Next.js Route Handlers";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-2">API Calls & Server Endpoints</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400">
      Astro API endpoints are like Next.js Route Handlers. They live in
      <code class="text-purple-300"> src/pages/api/*.ts</code> and export
      <code class="text-purple-300"> GET</code>, <code class="text-purple-300">POST</code>,
      etc. handler functions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-purple-400">
      1. Build-Time Data Fetching (SSG)
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
      In Astro, you can fetch data directly in the frontmatter of any page. This
      runs at build time for static pages.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-6">
      <pre class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono text-gray-300 mb-4 overflow-x-auto">// src/pages/example.astro
---
// This runs at build time, not on every request
const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
const data = await response.json();
---
&lt;div&gt;&#123;data.title&#125;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">
        In Next.js, this is equivalent to fetching in a Server Component or using
        <code class="text-blue-300"> getStaticProps</code> in Pages Router.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-purple-400">
      2. Server-Side Data Fetching (SSR)
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
      Use <code class="text-purple-300">export const prerender = false</code> to
      render data on every request.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-6">
      <pre class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono text-gray-300 mb-4 overflow-x-auto">---
export const prerender = false;
const res = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
const data = await res.json();
---</pre>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">
        In Next.js, this is equivalent to a dynamic Server Component or
        <code class="text-blue-300"> getServerSideProps</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-purple-400">
      3. API Endpoints
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
      Astro API endpoints work like Next.js Route Handlers. Here is the comparison:
    </p>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3 text-purple-400">Astro</h3>
        <pre class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono text-gray-300 overflow-x-auto">// src/pages/api/hello.ts
import type &#123; APIRoute &#125; from "astro";

export const prerender = false;

export const GET: APIRoute = async (&#123; request, cookies, redirect &#125;) => &#123;
  return new Response(JSON.stringify(&#123; message: "Hello" &#125;), &#123;
    status: 200,
    headers: &#123; "Content-Type": "application/json" &#125;,
  &#125;);
&#125;;</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3 text-blue-400">Next.js</h3>
        <pre class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono text-gray-300 overflow-x-auto">// app/api/hello/route.ts
import &#123; NextResponse &#125; from "next/server";

export async function GET() &#123;
  return NextResponse.json(&#123; message: "Hello" &#125;);
&#125;;</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-purple-400">
      4. Try the API Endpoints
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-400 mb-6">
      These endpoints are live on this server. Click to test them:
    </p>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      <a
        href="/api/hello"
        target="_blank"
        class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-4 hover:border-purple-500 transition-colors text-center"
      >
        <div class="text-purple-400 font-semibold mb-1">GET /api/hello</div>
        <div class="text-xs text-gray-500">Returns JSON greeting</div>
      </a>
      <a
        href="/api/session"
        target="_blank"
        class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-4 hover:border-purple-500 transition-colors text-center"
      >
        <div class="text-purple-400 font-semibold mb-1">GET /api/session</div>
        <div class="text-xs text-gray-500">Returns session status</div>
      </a>
      <div class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-4 text-center opacity-75">
        <div class="text-purple-400 font-semibold mb-1">POST /api/login</div>
        <div class="text-xs text-gray-500">Use LoginForm component</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key Differences from Next.js</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-300">
      <li class="flex gap-2">
        <span class="text-purple-400">-&gt;</span>
        <strong>Runtime:</strong> Astro endpoints run on the server (Node.js, Deno, or Edge).
        Next.js Route Handlers run on Edge or Node.js.
      </li>
      <li class="flex gap-2">
        <span class="text-purple-400">-&gt;</span>
        <strong>SSR opt-in:</strong> In Astro, you need <code>prerender = false</code>. In Next.js
        App Router, routes are dynamic by default.
      </li>
      <li class="flex gap-2">
        <span class="text-purple-400">-&gt;</span>
        <strong>Response format:</strong> Astro uses the Web Fetch API
        (<code>Response</code>, <code>Request</code>). Next.js provides
        <code>NextResponse</code> helpers.
      </li>
      <li class="flex gap-2">
        <span class="text-purple-400">-&gt;</span>
        <strong>Cookies:</strong> Astro provides <code>Astro.cookies</code> in pages and
        <code>cookies</code> in API routes. Next.js uses
        <code>cookies()</code> from <code>next/headers</code>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
